>Fielding</a></b><b>�(Minister\nof Finance):</b> I have a message from Her Honour the Lieutenant Governor,\nwhich I would like to table. ","index":"00370","speaker":"Scott Fielding"},{"html":"<b>Madam\nSpeaker:</b> Please stand for the reading of the message. ","index":"00371","speaker":""},{"html":"����� To the\nSpeaker of the Legislative Assembly, I have been informed of a proposed bill,\nThe Interim Appropriation Act, 2021, which will provide interim authority to\nmake expenditures from the Consolidated Fund effective April 1st, 2021, pending\napproval of the appropriation act, 2021. ","index":"00372","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The\nbill also provides for payments to develop or acquire inventory and against\ncertain liabilities accrued and unpaid as of March 31st, 2021. The bill will\nalso provide a portion of commitment authority for future years. ","index":"00373","speaker":""},{"html":"����� I\nrecommend the proposed bill to the Legislative Assembly. ","index":"00374","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Please\nbe seated. ","index":"00375","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The House\nwill now resolve into Committee of Supply to consider the resolutions\nrespecting the Interim Supply bill. ","index":"00376","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Mr.\nDeputy Speaker, please take the chair. ","index":"00377","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson (Doyle Piwniuk):</b> Will the Committee of Supply please come to\norder. We have before us the�for us�our consideration for resolution respecting\nthe Interim Supply bill. ","index":"00378","speaker":"Doyle Piwniuk"},{"html":"����� The\nfirst resolution, pertaining to part A, Operating Expenditures, for the Interim\nSupply, reads as follows: ","index":"00379","speaker":""},{"html":"����� RESOLVED\nthat there be granted to Her Majesty, for the fiscal year ending March 31st,\n2022, as a sum not exceeding $11,772,882,000, being 75&nbsp; per&nbsp; cent of\nthe total amount set out in the 2020 Estimates, including Supplementary\nEstimates, for the purposes set out for part A, Operating Expenditures, for\nthose Estimates. ","index":"00380","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Does\nthe minister have opening comments? No. Does the official opposition Finance\ncritic have any opening comments? No.","index":"00381","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>����� </b>The\nfloor is open for questions. Is there any questions? ","index":"00382","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>����� </b>Okay,\nthe honourable member for Fort Garry. ","index":"00383","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Mark </b><b><a name=\"_Toc67385150\">Wasyliw</a></b><b>�(Fort\nGarry):</b> I'm wondering if the minister can tell us: So, last spring, he\nappropriated $1 billion, and then he came back two more times, $577 million and\nanother more recent $450 million, so a little over $2 billion.","index":"00384","speaker":"Mark Wasyliw"},{"html":"����� I'm\nwondering if the minister can tell us how much of that $2 billion has gone\nunspent? ","index":"00385","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Hon.\nScott </b><b><a name=\"_Toc67385151\">Fielding</a></b><b>�(Minister\nof Finance):</b> The reason why there was three budgetary bills: the first one,\nof course, was the expenditures on COVID relief. The second bill was related to\nmonies that were flowing out, so through the safe start agreement we got\nmonies�as an example, $106 million that had to flow out through\n'numicipalities,' so we needed a second budgetary bill. The third appropriation\nwas to enhance some of the support programs that were in place. ","index":"00386","speaker":"Scott Fielding"},{"html":"����� And so\nall that money�and potentially more�would be spent by year end. ","index":"00387","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nWasyliw:</b> So just to clarify with the minister, all $2 billion are going to\nbe spent by March 31st? Or will there be a significant amount unspent by March\n31st of this year, and how much will be unspent by March&nbsp;31st, 2021? ","index":"00388","speaker":"Mark Wasyliw"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nFielding:</b> Yes. We're on track to have somewhere around a $2‑billion\ndeficit. We'll be bringing the Q3&nbsp; report out later that gives your\nestimates in terms of where we'll land the year, for the most part, but\nobviously we wouldn't ask for additional appro�priation bill�which we all voted\nin this House last week�if we didn't anticipate spending that money.","index":"00389","speaker":"Scott Fielding"},{"html":"<b>*</b>\n(15:00)","index":"00390","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nWasyliw:</b> I'm wondering if the minister can tell us how much of the close to\n$900&nbsp;million in the rainy day fund has gone unspent, and will all of it be\nspent before March 31st, 2021? ","index":"00391","speaker":"Mark Wasyliw"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nFielding:</b> Well, we won't make the same mistakes that the NDP made of\ndraining the rainy day fund. Thank goodness we had the foresight to have\nadditional monies as of March. ","index":"00392","speaker":"Scott Fielding"},{"html":"There was a time where we couldn't access the capital markets like every\nother provincial govern�ment. That has changed. We use a combination of using\nthings like the rainy day fund, debt financing, as well as revenues we bring in\nfrom the government.","index":"00393","speaker":""},{"html":"����� We\nhave committed to tap into the rainy day fund before the end of the fiscal\nyear. ","index":"00394","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Hon. Jon </b><b><a name=\"_Toc67385152\">Gerrard</a></b><b>�(River\nHeights):</b> To the minister, as of September 30th, the federal government had\ncontributed an extra $648&nbsp;million to the Province, above what had been\ncommitted earlier.","index":"00395","speaker":"Jon Gerrard"},{"html":"����� Can\nthe minister tell us whether there have been additional funds come in from the\nfederal government since September 30th? ","index":"00396","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nFielding:</b> Yes, it was an important agreement that was established through\nthe premiers, as well as through the federal governme